This insect bears a deceptive resemblance to Ο. circumducta, Boh., but it may be at once distinguished from that species by the more elongate third joint of the antennae (in 0. circumducta the third joint is shorter than the second); it is also smaller, with shorter antennae and a narrower annulus to the elytra, the latter not at all gibbous anteriorly, almost smooth at the apex, and not broadly subtruncate behind in the male. Numerous closely allied South-American species have been described by Boheman. We figure an example from Bugaba.
